    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, i've been having some trouble with my sourdough starter lately. i keep the temperature steady at around 75F but the rise is really inconsistent from day to day. could you explain the relationship between the wild yeast and the lactic acid bacteria in the fermentation process? like, how do they interact to affect the dough's structure?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Wild yeast and lactic acid bacteria (LAB) are the essential partners in sourdough fermentation, each contributing vital functions to your starter. The wild yeast consumes sugars and produces carbon dioxide, which is what causes the leavening and rise in your dough. Simultaneously, the LAB metabolize those sugars to produce various organic acids, primarily lactic and acetic acid. These acids are crucial because they lower the pH, which strengthens the gluten network in the dough, leading to better structure and a characteristic tangy flavor.",
      "source": "target",
